orations of her own writings, from Inside (1969) and ‘The Laugh of the Medusa’ (1975) up to the present. Royle’s book will be useful to students and academics coming to Cixous’s work for the first time, but it will also appeal to readers interested in contemporary literature, creative writing, life writing, narrative theory, deconstruction, psychoanalysis, trauma studies, feminism, queer theory, ecology, drawing and painting.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aLiterature Studies 2021. 4aShakespeare 2020. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aCixous.  aCreative writing.  aDerrida.  aDreaming.  aFreud.  aLewis Carroll.  aLiterature.  aRealism.  aShakespeare.  aUnidentifiable literary object.1 aPrenowitz, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoyle, Nicholas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packagez978311128248040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152614067840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526140678423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526140678/original  a978-3-11-128248-0  Manchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packageb2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles